# &nbsp;

# So how do we fix this?

---

# What the demo environment _became_?

???

Basically, I took that list I made of what the demo environment _was_
And I did all of the opposite

--

- ~~complete app ecosystem (all apps)~~


--

  _only_ the app being demoed (WebValve)

???

We use WebValve locally. Why not in demo?

--

- ~~sanitized, subsetted data (think: stage)~~

???

The most common issue was TestTrack getting out of sync.
And the sanitizer/subsetter was a common source of build failures.
But, also, customer data changes over time!
Why walk into a sales demo with something we can't predict?

--

  long-lived database with generated "personas"

???

We maintain user seeds locally. Why not use them for demos?

--

  "CleverSequence"

???

This was the biggest part of the project
rewrite the way that FB sequences work
so that Factories can pick up where they left off.

--

- ~~deployed every weekend~~

--

  continuously deployed <img height="20" src="data:image/png;base64,">

--

  with browser-based tests that step through real sales demos!

--

  wired up to Sentry and DataDog for observaility

--

- ~~maintained by B4B/B4A engineering~~

--

  maintained by _everyone_

???

This is the most controversial idea.

---

# &nbsp;
# &nbsp;
# Why _everyone_?

???

I didn't want to approach this saying, hey here's a new responsibility,
you HAVE to take this on. Sorry.

Rather, when I stepped back and looked, what I saw was a tragedy of the commons.
It was _already_ a failure in collective ownership, with the burden saddled on just a few individuals.
And so I wanted to approach this as an incentives problem.
Who has the incentive to maintain something different than everything else we maintain?
With only a handful of customers and use cases?

And, so, I thought, when you make it the same as everything else
A continuously-deployed production instance with real SLAs and observability,
And tests that step through common sales demos and fail builds if we break them,
, suddenly,
everyone is maintaining it without even trying.

So when I say _everyone_ maintains it, I'm not saying everyone is _responsible_ for it.
But by doing what we do every day, we _all_ help _maintain_ the demo app.
